"thumbnail", "type": "image", "width": 75, "height": 75}], "section_name": "U.S.", "word_count": "1295", "source": "The New York Times", "subsection_name": null, "lead_paragraph": "Since October 2004, more than half of children who did not have lawyers were deported, while only one in 10 children who had lawyers were sent back.", "pub_date": "2016-08-20T20:08:55+0000", "news_desk": "National", "headline": {"print_headline": "In Immigration Court, Children Must Serve as Own Lawyers", "main": "It\u2019s Children Against Federal Lawyers in Immigration Court"}, "print_page": "10", "snippet": "Since October 2004, more than half of children who did not have lawyers were deported, while only one in 10 children who had lawyers were sent back....", "_id": "57b8b8de95d0e021d7981c1f", "slideshow_credits": null, "abstract": "Children who are accused of violating United States immigration laws, civil offense, do not have right to legal representation in court; activists say situation has resulted in more than half of all children seeking asylum in United States ending up being deported; legal experts say American government is under no obligation to provide children who are not citizens with representation, but class-action lawsuit filed by ACLU and other civil rights organizations will attempt to address gap in laws."}